      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey quick question, i'm running a small clothing boutique and i keep hearing about \"inventory turnover ratio\". how do i actually calculate that and what does a low number mean for my shop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can calculate the Inventory Turnover Ratio by dividing your **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)** by your **Average Inventory**. For your boutique, this means taking the total cost of all the clothes you sold over a specific period and dividing it by the average number of items you had on the shelf.\n\nA **low number** is a major red flag for your shop, as it suggests your inventory is sitting stagnant and not moving. It implies you are overstocking, which ties up cash and risks obsolescence if trends shift. Conversely, a high number is good, but only if it's not so high that you're constantly buying new stock before you can sell the old, which would just mean you're flipping things too fast and missing out on the profit margin of selling a few high-end pieces.\n\nTo fix this, you need to audit your stock and perhaps run a clearance sale to move the slow items.",
